[What a challenge to treat these sheep, or to allow the disease to
run its course and consequently potentially lose portions of this
herd! With other animals such as rabbits capable of transmitting this
mite, this is even more of a challenge.

To effectively reach the mite in the skin requires dipping several
times to get rid of the mite. These mites burrow into the skin and
cause pain and itching in many cases, but almost always hair loss.

The following web site provides excellent pictures of the variety of
burrowing skin mites:
<http://www.google.fr/images?hl=3Dfr&xhr=3Dt&q=3Dpsoroptes&cp=3D9&um=3D1&=ie=3DUTF-8&source=3Duniv&sa=3DX&ei=3DaqmDTcyFMYOxhQeom6zCBA&sqi=3D2&ved=3D=0CCgQsAQ&biw=1005&bih=561>
- Mod.TG

The interactive HealthMap/ProMED map for the Similkameen in British
Columbia, Canada, is available at:
<http://healthmap.org/r/0BgA> - CopyEd.EJP]

